post_text:
Governor DeWine announced today that all schools will be closed for 3 weeks and will be re-evaluated after that. Franklin Local School District will follow that order and be closed Monday, March 16th through April 3rd. While we are closed, everyone is advised to not congregate together so the disease spread slows down. All athletic and theater practices will cease after tomorrow. Children can be carriers so they should avoid visiting with or staying with older adults who can easily contract the disease. Instructional packets will be sent home with students tomorrow. Grades 6-12 students will have access to some lessons that are downloaded to their iPads. Those links are also on our website under student links. This is an unprecedented global event. We can get through this together.
Sharon McDermott, Superintendent

post_text: Eighth Grade Awards and Promotion Ceremony will be held at 11:15 (note:time change) at Philo Junior High School on May 23rd. This is a different format than the past few years… it is NOT a FORMAL dress Graduation Ceremony. We plan to celebrate our 8th Graders’ accomplishments this school year and promotion to Philo High School!!! We will host an 8th Grade Dance on the night of May 23rd at Philo High School (7PM-9PM). This will be an informal dance and “normal” PJH dress code will apply (2 inch straps on tops and knee length for all shorts, skirts, dresses); however, this dance can be as formal or informal as the student chooses, as long as the dress code requirements are met. 8th Grade students may invite 1 Philo Junior High student to accompany them. Any non-PJH 7th or 8th grade student must be approved by Mr. Preston.

post_text:
Time is quickly approaching for the 2nd annual Franklin Local Feeds Families community project. The purpose of this event is to help replenish the food banks in our area. In order to make this a success for the second straight year, we are asking fans who attend the Philo - Maysville boys basketball game on January 7th to help by bringing canned or non-perishable food items or make a monetary donation; this year, the food or monetary donation is in addition to the ticket price.
During last year’s game, fans from the Franklin and Maysville Local School Districts donated over 2,300 food items that were distributed to food banks that serve both school districts. We are again asking for your help to help those in need. If you have any questions about this event or would like to volunteer your time, please contact Frank Van Kirk at 697-7317 or email at frank.vankirk@omeresa.net

Per Superintendent Sharon McDermott:

The Franklin Local School District has a Permanent Improvement Levy on tomorrow’s ballot. The funds will be used for Safe Buses, Safe Children, Safe Buildings, and Technology for Tomorrow’s Jobs. We have Pride in Our Past with passing the Permanent Improvement Levy every five years since 1980. We are Proud of Today with having the highest rated district report card in the county, a state-bound Philo High School band and our varsity football team is in the state playoffs. We are Preparing for our Future. Please remember to vote tomorrow, November 5th! Thank you!

Per Superintendent Sharon McDermott,

First, the Philo Electrics Varsity Football team will play Sheridan on Friday, October 11th at 7:30 PM. A large crowd is expected for this Electric match-up. To avoid standing in the long ticket line at the gate, purchase pre-sale tickets at Philo High School, Philo Junior High, and Roseville Elementary during school hours. Pre-sale tickets can also be purchased at Citizens National Bank in Duncan Falls. Tickets are $5 for adults and $2 for students.

Secondly, to show our support of Teacher and Coach Matt Brown, the football parents have asked for everyone to wear their Kicking for Coach Shirt to the game. Shirts are still available at the Village Gift Shop in Duncan Falls with the proceeds going to Coach Brown. Carnations will be sold at each gate for $2.00 with all proceeds going to Coach Brown to help with his expenses.

I hope to see you at the game Friday night!

post_text:
Count Week 2013!
Do you know what Count Week is? Attendance is always important; however, October 7th – 11th is Count Week and that is the week which determines state funding for districts by counting the number of students who are enrolled and in school each day. It is extremely important for our community and Franklin Local School District that your child is in attendance each school day.

post_text:
FLCS
Focus:

Mr. Mosebrook’s Biology students created a classroom size food web out of yarn to demonstrate how living organisms in an ecosystem are connected.

Mrs. Woodard attended a Literacy Design Collaborative workshop sponsored by BFK to create a module for students to combine content knowledge with rigorous literary standards.

Mr. Michel and our juniors continued to give back to our community by providing supplemental groceries to 284 local families.

Mr. Foreman’s sophomore students are producing short films that deal with important issues facing today’s teens such as bullying, teen pregnancy, underage drinking, and drug use. The videos will be used to facilitate group discussions on making healthy choices.

Mrs. Spears continues to work with our seniors as they are completing their senior portfolios which are a required component for graduation.

A special Thanks to Barb McCutcheon who continues to provide healthy meals to students and staff!

post_text:
PHS
W.I.N. (What I Noticed) Report
Two PHS seniors were recognized Thursday evening at the Ohio School Boards Association Southeast Region Recognition Program. Tinh Le was honored as the region's most outstanding male student. Ashley McLean was honored as the region's most outstanding female student. The program has been going for 20 years and this was the first time that both outstanding students came from the same school!

Mr. Mull, Mrs. Swingle, Mrs. Graff, Mrs. Harris, Mr. Boysel and Mrs. Pollock have worked very hard to help our students have an outstanding Homecoming experience. Thank you.

Many teachers have provided helpful information to help improve students' 504 plans.

Teachers are working hard on their SLO development.

A big thanks goes out to our coaches of fall sports. We appreciate your willingness to help guide our students through sports.

post_text:
Franklin Local Schools earns audit award!

COLUMBUS — Franklin Local Community School and Franklin Local School District in Muskingum County received the Auditor of State Award for their clean audit reports, according to Auditor of State Dave Yost.

The Auditor of State Award is presented to local governments and school districts upon the completion of a financial audit. Entities that receive the award meet the following criteria of a “clean” audit report:

• The entity must file timely financial reports with the Auditor of State’s office in accordance with Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.

• The audit report does not contain any findings for recovery, material citations, material weaknesses, significant deficiencies, single audit findings or questioned costs.

Source: Zanesville Times Recorder

• The entity must file timely financial reports with the Auditor of State’s office in accordance with Generally Accepted Accounting Principles.

• The audit report does not contain any findings for recovery, material citations, material weaknesses, significant deficiencies, single audit findings or questioned costs.

Source: Zanesville Times Recorder
